# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-api-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] A server that acts as an API front-end receives API requests, enforces throttling and security policies, passes requests to the back-end service and then passes the response back to the requester.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] A gateway often includes a transformation engine to orchestrate and modify the requests and responses on the fly.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] A gateway can also provide functions such as collecting analytics data and providing caching.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] The gateway can provide the functionality to support authentication, authorization, security, audit and regulatory compliance.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] Functionality to monitor API usage and load (overall hits, completed transactions, number of data objects returned, amount of compute time and other internal resources consumed, the volume of data transferred).
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] This can include real-time API monitoring with alerts being raised directly or via a higher-level network management system, for instance, if the load on an API has become too great, as well as functionality to analyze historical data, such as transaction logs, to detect usage trends.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] Functionality can also be provided to create synthetic transactions that can be used to test the performance and behavior of API endpoints.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] The API provider can use the information gathered by the reporting and analytics functionality to optimize the API offering within an organization's overall continuous improvement process and define software Service-Level Agreements for APIs.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] Functionality to support charging for access to commercial APIs.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] This functionality can include support for setting up pricing rules based on usage, load and functionality, issuing invoices, and collecting payments, including multiple types of credit card payments.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] Several industry analysts have observed that the market size for API management solutions has been growing rapidly since the early 2010s.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] Gartner estimated the market size for API management to be $70 million in 2013, growing at 40% a year.
[src:azure-api-management/api-gateway] According to Forrester Research, in the US alone, annual spend on API management was $140 million in 2014, expected to grow to $660 million by 2020, with total global sales predicted to exceed a billion dollars by that year.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] The **OpenAPI Specification** (**OAS**), previously known as the **Swagger Specification**, is a specification for a machine-readable interface definition language for describing, producing, consuming and visualizing web services.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] Originally developed to support the Swagger framework, it became a separate project in 2015, overseen by the OpenAPI Initiative, an open-source collaboration project of the Linux Foundation.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] An OpenAPI Description (OAD) represents a formal description of an API that tools can use to generate code, documentation, test cases, and more.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] Swagger development began in early 2010 by Tony Tam, who was working at online dictionary company Wordnik.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] In March 2015, SmartBear Software acquired the open-source Swagger API specification from Reverb Technologies, Wordnik's parent company.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] In November 2015, SmartBear announced that it was donating the Swagger specification to a new organization called the OpenAPI Initiative, under the sponsorship of the Linux Foundation.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] Other founding member companies included 3scale, Apigee, Capital One, Google, IBM, Intuit, Microsoft, PayPal, and Restlet.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] On 1 January 2016, the Swagger specification was renamed the OpenAPI Specification (OAS) and was moved to a new GitHub repository.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] Two somewhat similar technologies, MuleSoft's RESTful API Modeling Language (RAML) and Apiary's API Blueprint, had been developed around the same time as what was then still called the Swagger Specification.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] The producers of both formats later joined the OpenAPI Initiative: Apiary in 2016 and MuleSoft in 2017.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] In July 2017, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.0.0 of its specification.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] In February 2021, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.1.0.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] In September 2025, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.2.0 of the OAS.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] Notable features include structured tags, first-class streaming media type support, support for arbitrary HTTP methods, clearer example semantics for serializations, OAuth2 device flow and metadata enhancements, and clarified path templating and routing semantics.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] The OAS describes the format for OpenAPI Descriptions (OADs), which can be used by a variety of applications, libraries, and tools.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] Applications can use OADs to automatically generate documentation of methods, parameters and data models.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] This helps keep the documentation, client libraries and source code in sync.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] When an OAD is used to generate source code stubs for servers, the process is called scaffolding.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] The paradigm of agreeing on an API contract first and then programming business logic afterwards, in contrast to coding the program first and then writing a retrospective description of its behavior as the contract, is called contract-first development.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] Since the interface is determined before any code is written, downstream developers can mock the server behavior and start testing right away.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] In this sense, contract-first development is also a practice of shift-left testing.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Specification is language-agnostic.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] With OpenAPI's declarative resource specification, clients can understand and consume services without knowledge of server implementation or access to the server code.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Initiative sponsored APIStrat from 2017 to 2019, converting it into the API Specifications Confererence (ASC) from 2020 to 2022.
[src:azure-api-management/openapi-specification] Starting in 2023, the initiative has instead sponsored OpenAPI tracks at multiple conferences throughout the year.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:azure-api-management/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:azure-api-management/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:azure-api-management/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
